Spring:
  The Spring Framework is a lightweight, open-source Java framework used to build enterprise-level applications. 
  It mainly provides infrastructure support so you can focus on business logic.
Benefits of Spring Framework:
  1. Loose Coupling - Classes are independent → easy to maintain
  2. Easy Testing - Supports unit and integration testing
  3. Lightweight - uses POJO
  4. Flexible & Modular - uses only required modules
  5. Reduces Boilerplate Code - replace XML's over annotations
  6. Scalable & Enterprise Ready - Used in large-scale systems
  7. Integration friendly - intergrates with DB, API's and messaging system.
Limitations of Spring Framework:
  1. learning curve - Beginners struggle with Annotations, Configurations and AOP concepts
  2. Complexity in Large Projects - Too many annotations can confuse and Debugging becomes harder
  3. Performance Overhead - Reflection & proxy usage adds slight overhead
  4. Configuration Overload (without Spring Boot) - xml based config was heavy 
  5. Hidden Magic (Auto Configuration) - hard to understand whats happening
  
Core Features of Spring Framework:
Spring Core: The Spring Core is the foundation module of the Spring Framework.
    It provides:
                IoC (Inversion of Control) Container
                Dependency Injection (DI)
                Bean lifecycle management
                Everything in Spring (MVC, Boot, Security) depends on this
